##### [¬ß](#at-compiletime)At compiletime

**Note: Alignment at compiletime is experimental and subject to change. See the [tracking issue](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/104203) for details.**

At compiletime, the compiler may not know where a value will end up in memory. Calling this function on a pointer created from a reference at compiletime will only return `true` if the pointer is guaranteed to be aligned. This means that the pointer is never aligned if cast to a type with a stricter alignment than the reference‚Äôs underlying allocation.

```
#![feature(const_pointer_is_aligned)]

// On some platforms, the alignment of primitives is less than their size.
#[repr(align(4))]
struct AlignedI32(i32);
#[repr(align(8))]
struct AlignedI64(i64);

const _: () = {
    let data = AlignedI32(42);
    let ptr = &data as *const AlignedI32;
    assert!(ptr.is_aligned());

    // At runtime either `ptr1` or `ptr2` would be aligned, but at compiletime neither is aligned.
    let ptr1 = ptr.cast::<AlignedI64>();
    let ptr2 = ptr.wrapping_add(1).cast::<AlignedI64>();
    assert!(!ptr1.is_aligned());
    assert!(!ptr2.is_aligned());
};
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0A%23!%5Bfeature(const_pointer_is_aligned)%5D%0A%0A//+On+some+platforms,+the+alignment+of+primitives+is+less+than+their+size.%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++%23%5Brepr(align(4))%5D%0A++++struct+AlignedI32(i32);%0A++++%23%5Brepr(align(8))%5D%0A++++struct+AlignedI64(i64);%0A++++%0A++++const+_:+()+=+%7B%0A++++++++let+data+=+AlignedI32(42);%0A++++++++let+ptr+=+%26data+as+*const+AlignedI32;%0A++++++++assert!(ptr.is_aligned());%0A++++%0A++++++++//+At+runtime+either+%60ptr1%60+or+%60ptr2%60+would+be+aligned,+but+at+compiletime+neither+is+aligned.%0A++++++++let+ptr1+=+ptr.cast::%3CAlignedI64%3E();%0A++++++++let+ptr2+=+ptr.wrapping_add(1).cast::%3CAlignedI64%3E();%0A++++++++assert!(!ptr1.is_aligned());%0A++++++++assert!(!ptr2.is_aligned());%0A++++%7D;%0A%7D&version=nightly&edition=2021)

Due to this behavior, it is possible that a runtime pointer derived from a compiletime pointer is aligned, even if the compiletime pointer wasn‚Äôt aligned.

```
